results.notes: Growing among hardwood leaf litter. Pileipellis composed of rounded cells. Clamps present in the stipe trama and in the lamellar trama. On a large sandstone bedrock outcrop. Specifically on a weathered, crumbly north-facing slab.

Thallus not evident. Apothecia dispersed to crowded, plane to flexuous, margins white, raised to finally slightly reduced, C+O weak, K+Y strong, UV-(bad light, so not confirmed), somewhat cracked (sensu Sliwa 2007) or discontinuous, disks pale to pinkish orange, always epruinose. Amphithecium with thick layer of POL+ small crystals that are insoluble in K, and thick algal layer. Epihymenium with dark reddish brown granules, with thick layer of POL+ small crystals not spread through hymenium (ie: not dispersa-type), with pigments and crystals soluble in K.

results.notes:
Found by Christian Schwarz. Growing on Douglas fir needles.

Dry caps about 1cm across, stems 2-3cm.

Basidia 4-spored, ~20×5. Spores 6.5-8 × 2.5-4. Hymenial cystidia up to 23 × 6, mixed with basidia, found everywhere with basidia, not only on gill edge. Pileipeillis a dense mass, difficult to disentangle, made of branching diverticulae; capitate pileocystidia small, scattered. Hyphae of stipitipellis mostly smooth, but some are diverticulate; capitate caulocystidia are numerous.

The description of H. pseudolactea in Antonin & Noordelos matches quite well, except for the abundance of all kinds of cystidia, which we cannot confirm, and especially for the size of hymenial cystidia, 25-65 × 6-12, which is much larger than what we have.

results.notes:
Growing on fern rhizomes.

Basidia ~25×8. Spores 7-8.5 × 4-5.5. Cheilocystidia up to 46×12.

Microscopically, this species is hardly distinguishable from M. leptocephala. (There may be significant differences in hypoderm+proper trama, to which I haven’t been paying much attention.) Growth on ferns is not necessarily a distinguisher (why wouldn’t leptocephala grow on ferns?), but long fragile stems (combined with the habitat) are probably enough to tell the two species apart even without the habitat info.

M. fragillima may not be as rare as it appears. See Observation 349611 from Bay Area a weak earlier.
